We all seems to agree on one thing...these businesses are a terrible investment. <br><BR><font size=1>13:18 10-30-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#000000>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#000000><font class="bfont"><B>Pistone</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#000000' ><font class="bfont">I agree with Mike&#39;s statement.  It won&#39;t replace console games, but its enough to hurt the gaming market.  Think about when mp3&#39;s started getting big, and the CD market.  Its enough that I certainly wouldn&#39;t invest. <br><BR><font size=1>00:25 10-27-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#333333>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#333333><font class="bfont"><B>mc9457</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#333333' ><font class="bfont">Jedi and Asph - don&#39;t put words in where they weren&#39;t.<br />
<br />
I said that the downloadable games would cause problems long term for the used video game market - not that they would be the end of physical units. <br><BR><font size=1>00:11 10-27-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#000000>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#000000><font class="bfont"><B>Pistone</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#000000' ><font class="bfont">Scott, you shouldn&#39;t try to get too creative with your investing unless you&#39;re planning on putting hours into it.  You should read "A Random Walk Down Wall Street" by Burton G. Malkiel if you&#39;re serious in investing.<br />
<br />
His basic thesis is that you should invest in an index fund that tracks the market, and just leave your money there.  Constantly moving your money means you incur transaction costs which eats into your returns.  Stocks earn roughly 8-9% annual returns if you invest long term (they&#39;re highly volatile in the short term, which can make you either very rich or very poor quickly) so they are a safe investment in the long term.<br />
<br />
The other thing Malkiel emphasizes is that these investment firms are unlikely to help you make more money than you would on your own in an index fund.  Data shows that no investment firm consistently beats the market, and any that do charge you fees which eat into your returns making you worse off than you would have been if you didn&#39;t use them.  Think about it, investors are very smart people.  If one investment firm consistently outperformed the market, everyone would use it and the others wouldn&#39;t exist.  Additionally, if the investment firm could consistently beat the market, they&#39;d be investing themselves instead of offering advice. <br><BR><font size=1>17:02 10-26-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#333333>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#333333><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#333333' ><font class="bfont"><blockquote><i>since the life span of a console is 2 to 3 years.</i></blockquote>Um... average lifespan of a console is 5 years or so.  <br><BR><font size=1>13:34 10-26-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#000000>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#000000><font class="bfont"><B>Asphalizo</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#000000' ><font class="bfont">Also of Note is that the PS2 will still be highly sought after since Sony has decided to dump backwards compatibility in the newest version of the  PS3.  This only the latest of many decisions made by Sony to separate the PS3 from the PS2. AKA, Sony is stupid.  Why would a company totally alienate the largest selling console ever? <br><BR><font size=1>13:18 10-26-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#333333>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#333333><font class="bfont"><B>Asphalizo</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#333333' ><font class="bfont">B-Dawg is right.  The downloadable game service is only doing well do to the small game sizes and the serious retro-invasion we&#39;ve been seeing.  NES games are like 20 KB or less. SNES are a few MB if that. N64 get a little bigger but the size jump came when games left the cartridges and went the way of the CD/DVD. The CD/DVD game the programmers the freedom to be "sloppy" in their allocation of space. Textures and sound were thrown on disc without compression simply because they could.  Only recently with the 3rd gen technology has the need to think wisely in programming games arrived.<br />
<br />
However, in spite of that, the downloadable gaming on the PC has begun to pick up speed.  Maybe its because of the PC&#39;s ease for upgrade or something else but sources like Valve&#39;s Steam have seen a steady demand for downloadable games.  Steam recenlty made much of the ID library available to download including titles like Doom 1 & 2, Quake 1 & 2, and Wolfenstein 3D. These are retro titles but the Orange Box, valve&#39;s latest gaming compilation, is also available for download and has seen a majority of people downloading it rather than go to the store.<br />
<br />
Consoles will not see this happen for at least 2 more generations or more.  Console work will with a physically library since the life span of a console is 2 to 3 years. <br><BR><font size=1>13:15 10-26-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#000000>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#000000><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#000000' ><font class="bfont">Video games will not go to a download only service any time soon. It makes no sense. A modern video game on the Xbox360 takes up 8GB of space, and 20-50GB for a PS3 game(due to lazy programming). My Xbox360 gaming collection is already 15-20 games(I haven&#39;t counted recently, so lets just assume 15). 15 x 8 = 120GB... and that&#39;s only 2 years into a console&#39;s life cycle. Consider how big the hard drive would have to be for this, and on top of that, what would happen if/when the hard drive inevitably fails. Physical media may cost a little bit more, but it is much more convenient to store games on than massive hard drives. Plus it keeps the retail outlets happy (where they have to sell hardware and accessories).<br />
<br />
VC and XBLA games are minuscule in size, and hence they can be downloadable. Definitely difficult to compare these to an actual retail game. <br><BR><font size=1>12:33 10-26-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#333333>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#333333><font class="bfont"><B>mc9457</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#333333' ><font class="bfont">"do NOT get involved with a partnership that is not structured as an LLC or LLP or LP or some sort of joint venture/sole proprietorship"<br />
<br />
should read<br />
<br />
"do NOT get involved with a partnership that is not structured as an LLC or LLP or LP and do not get involved with some sort of joint venture/sole proprietorship"<br />
 <br><BR><font size=1>12:10 10-26-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#000000>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#000000><font class="bfont"><B>mc9457</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#000000' ><font class="bfont">Its a gamble imo.  Not sure I would invest in it for 2 reasons:<br />
<br />
The growth period is over for these type of industries.  Normally by the time the average investor jumps into a growing industry its done growing - and is either plateuing or on its decline.<br />
<br />
There has been a lot of talk over the past year of making games forced to register to a system in order to play (those who played Phantasy Star Online for the Dreamcast know the system).  Combine this with the increase in popularity of downloadable games (Wii Virtual Console, XBox Live Arcade) and it looks like trouble for the used video game industry long term.<br />
<br />
Finally my biggest concern with this model is the glut of product it seems these stores have.  You never see them with empty shelves and rarely see them turn away product.  Recently they stopped dealing in used DVDs locally and have 4 racks full of used DVDs that they can&#39;t move.  Thats inventory space that could be better used that they can&#39;t/won&#39;t get rid of.<br />
<br />
Now I have heard from various sources (including gaming stores like Troll and Toad) that this is the way to go.  But I&#39;d really look into it before investing.  What seems like a good investment now may not be in a year or two.  And investing in store front is a lot risker then investing in stocks or a mutual fund.<br />
<br />
Whatever you end up doing, get the partnership/corporation agreement in writing before investing.  Make sure you have your attorney and accountant review it before signing anything.  Make SURE you are protected from anything that goes wrong with the store (ie make sure its an LLC or corporate structure); do NOT get involved with a partnership that is not structured as an LLC or LLP or LP or some sort of joint venture/sole proprietorship.  Understand that you, as an owner, will be personally guaranteeing any debt that the company incurs and the banks will come after you when the company defaults.<br />
<br />
Its a risk - make sure the returns justify the risk you are taking.  If they can&#39;t beat out a mutual fund return for the dollars you are investing, its a poor investment.<br />
<br />
So my steps to you would be:<br />
<br />
Get an attorney<br />
Get an accountant<br />
Get a financial advisor<br />
<br />
Talk it over with all 3 of them before making any decision. <br><BR><font size=1>12:07 10-26-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#333333>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#333333><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#333333' ><font class="bfont">The Xbox has a TON of great games still, and is still a very capable console. I&#39;d buy a Xbox over a PS2 if I had neither simply for the unlimited hours I&#39;d get of Halo 2 online, plus Ninja Gaiden and other awesome games.<br />
